, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Speldhurst, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Orpington, London, England, United Kingdom":"Orpington, London, England, United Kingdom","Spelhurst Church, Tunbridge Wells, Kent, England":"Tunbridge Wells, Kent, England","All Saints Church, Hornchurch, Havering, London, England, United Kingdom":"All Saints Church, Hornchurch, Havering, London, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Gulby","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably a shortened form of English <b>Gooldsbury</b>, a variant of   Goldsborough  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Goldsborough","meanings":["English: habitational name from either of two places in North Yorkshire called Goldsborough. One, near Knaresborough, is named from the Old English personal name <i>Godel</i> + Old English <i>burh</i> ‘fortified place’. The other, near Whitby, is named from the Old English personal name <i>Golda</i> + <i>burh</i>."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William Gulby was born in 1370, in Speldhurst, Kent, England, United Kingdom as the son of Thomas Gulby. He married Agnes de Arderne about 1395, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1